03790nam a22005295i 9780520922952DE-B159720200707022542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200707t20001999cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209229527 a10.1525/97805209229522doi  a(DE-B1597)542989  a(OCoLC)1163878659  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPS310.I52bL56 2000 7aPOE0000002bisacsh04a811.009/8972211 aLincoln, Kenneth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSing with the Heart of a Bear :bFusions of Native and American Poetry, 1890-1999 /cKenneth Lincoln.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2000] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (461 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tONE. Native Poetics -- tTWO. Aboriginal American Texts -- tTHREE. Indian Poetry in Our Time -- tFOUR. (Native) American Verses -- tFIVE. Mythic Mothers -- tSIX. Adamic Savages -- tSEVEN. Reimagining the Garden -- tEIGHT. Seer, Shaman, Clown -- tNINE. Blood Sisters -- tTEN. Millennial Women -- tELEVEN. Mixed Rebirth -- tTWELVE. A Terrible Innocence: Forche -- tSELECTED BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExamining contemporary poetry by way of ethnicity and gender, Kenneth Lincoln tracks the Renaissance invention of the Wild Man and the recurrent Adamic myth of the lost Garden. He discusses the first anthology of American Indian verse, The Path on the Rainbow (1918), which opened Jorge Luis Borges' university surveys of American literature, to thirty-five contemporary Indian poets who speak to, with, and against American mainstream bards. From Whitman's free verse, through the Greenwich Village Renaissance (sandwiched between the world wars) and the post-apocalyptic Beat incantations, to transglobal questions of tribe and verse at the century's close, Lincoln shows where we mine the mother lode of New World voices, what distinguishes American verse, which tales our poets sing and what inflections we hear in the rhythms, pitches, and parsings of native lines.Lincoln presents the Lakota concept of "singing with the heart of a bear" as poetry which moves through an artist. He argues for a fusion of estranged cultures, tribal and émigré, margin and mainstream, in detailing the ethnopoetics of Native American translation and the growing modernist concern for a "native" sense of the "makings" of American verse. This fascinating work represents a major new effort in understanding American and Native American literature, spirituality, and culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Jul 2020) 0aAmerican poetryxIndian authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican poetryxIndian influences. 0aIndians in literature. 0aIndians of North AmericaxIntellectual life. 7aPOETRY / General.2bisacsh0 cprintz978052021890140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520922952423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520922952.jpg  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles